Regardless of the concentration of cysteine, AuNP-CysA supported cysteine solution can detect Cu2+ through colorimetric sensing, because cysteine is a chelator agent for Cu2+. Cu2+ can be connected with the chelating ring of cysteine by interacting with the amine and thiol groups of the cysteine molecules, which is accompanied by the color alternating of the AuNPs-CysA supported cysteine solution from royal blue to ruby red. Therefore, cysteine can be detached from the AuNP-CysA, leading to raise the bind energy of the AuNP-CysA, and in consequence, raising the intensity of the UV–Vis peak of AuNP-CysA supported cysteine in the presence of Cu2+. Moreover, methionine can also detect Cu2+, regarding to the fact that methionine is a chelator agent for Cu2 + . Methionine molecules can make a chelating ring around Cu2+ and form ionic binds through their carboxyl and amine groups. Detaching the electrostatic indications of the carboxyl groups of the methionine and the amine groups of AuNP-CysA to participate the methionine molecules in the Cu2+ chelating process is accompanied by color alternation of the AuNP-CysA supported methionine sensing solution (Fig. 8

                        ). Moreover, the AuNP-CysA detachment from methionine caused to increase the bind energy of AuNP-CysA which was decreased in the presence of methionine, leading to raise the UV–vis peak intensity of AuNP-CysA supported methionine in the presence of Cu2+ (Fig. 10
                        ).Fig. 11.

Regarding real sample evaluation, human urine sample were used, which are treated with several ions, Hg2+ and Cu2+ were evaluated in human urine sample by AuNPs-CysA supported cysteine solution. Apart from Cu2+, the color of the solution in the presence of the non-thiophilic ions was altered from pink to blue in the real sample, representing the AuNPs-CysA agglomeration by the electrostatic interactions between two amine groups of AuNP-CysA, while the interactions between the AuNPs-CysA and cysteine-cysteine complexes (electrostatic interplays between amine groups and carboxyl groups) are remained intact. Therefore, the presence of other ions except Hg2+ and Cu2+ caused to AuNPs-CysA agglomeration and changed the color of the solution from pink to blue. However, the color of the sensing solution was changed to ruby red, and sky blue in the presence of Cu2+, regarding to the chelating behavior of cysteine, and methionine for this ion, respectively (Fig. 18
                           ), and (Fig. 19
                           ). Therefore, Cu2+ can be detected in human urine samples, with LOD of 0.02 µg/ml.
